addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\""},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\\\"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\""},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\\\"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":1,"delta":"}\"}","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\\\"}\"}","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\\\"}\"}","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
{"aar_log_filter":{"content_index":0,"dropped_prefix_bytes":7098,"field":"thinking","message":"earlier repeated message_update events dropped","replaced_fields":2,"response_id":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","tail_bytes":0},"assistantMessageEvent":{"content":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","contentIndex":0,"partial":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"thinking":"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782814659300,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":20186,"output":1794,"totalTokens":21980}},"type":"thinking_end"},"message":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"thinking":"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782814659300,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":20186,"output":1794,"totalTokens":21980}},"type":"message_update"}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":1,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":20186,"output":1794,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21980,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":20186,"output":1794,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21980,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782814659300,"responseId":"gen-1782815559-i3qdoZuPa1a8sWxDahgH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the admitted evidence to make a vote. The prompt shows I'm council member C2 for case arb-ex10-20260630080125. I need to decide whether the proposition was \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\".\n\nThe proposition: \"Before January 1, 2027 at 00:00 PST, Polymarket launched an official fungible token: a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\"\n\nLooking at the \"Record\" section in the prompt:\n\n- Plaintiff argues that pUSD qualifies as an official fungible token:\n  * Fungibility: pUSD is a standard ERC-20 on Polygon, transferable, USDC-backed\n  * Official release: Polymarket's contracts page lists pUSD as CollateralToken proxy, Polymarket's pUSD documentation describes it\n  * Public communication: changelog entries from April 2026 announce pUSD as a new collateral token\n\n- Defendant argues it's not:\n  * pUSD is presented as part of \"technical collateral migration\" not a \"token launch\"\n  * The Help Center article calls it a \"technical layer underneath\" and describes the upgrade as \"Polymarket Exchange Upgrade\"\n  * \"Day to day, nothing changes\" and it's described as \"technical settlement layer\" - not a standalone token launched to market participants\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the \"preponderance of evidence\" standard.\n\nKey evidence points:\n\nPlaintiff evidence (PX-1 to PX-8, DX-1):\n- Official pUSD documentation: \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n- Official Contracts page: Lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy)\" with specific address\n- Changelog entries: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\" (April 17, 2026)\n- Changelog: \"CLOB V2 is live on production\" (April 28, 2026)\n- Migration guide: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n- Help Center article: \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nCritical language:\n- \"polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to pUSD\"\n- \"pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket\"\n- \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade... and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n- \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket\"\n- \"Day to day, nothing changes. You load funds, see a balance, trade, and withdraw. pUSD is the technical settlement layer underneath the same experience you're used to.\"\n\nThe definition specifically excludes: \"collaboration/community tokens\" but doesn't exclude \"collateral tokens\" - though the definition says \"official fungible token\" and then provides examples of what doesn't count (NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, collaboration/community tokens).\n\nThe key question is whether \"a new collateral token\" launched as part of an exchange upgrade qualifies as \"an official fungible token\" under the given definition.\n\nLooking at the record, Polymarket:\n1. Clearly launched a token called \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD\n2. Described it as a \"standard ERC-20 token on Polygon\"\n3. It was officially documented by Polymarket in multiple places\n4. It replaced USDC.e as the collateral token\n5. It has specific contract addresses\n6. It functions as a token within Polymarket's trading environment\n\nThe definition says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels\" - and all of this seems to apply to pUSD.\n\nBut the defendant argues that it's more accurate to say this was a technical collateral migration rather than a \"token launch.\" However, the language in the Polymarket documentation doesn't say \"technical collateral migration\" - they say they're shipping a \"new collateral token\" and identify the token as \"Polymarket USD\" or pUSD.\n\nThe prompt says: \"The current record already identifies the token that satisfies that definition: Polymarket USD, or pUSD.\"\n\nI need to decide whether this meets the standard.\n\nLooking at the evidence more closely:\n\n- The pUSD documentation says \"pUSD (Polymarket USD) is the collateral token used for all trading on Polymarket. It's a standard ERC-20 token on Polygon, backed by USDC.\"\n\n- The contracts page lists \"pUSD — CollateralToken (proxy) at 0xC011a7E12a19f7B1f670d46F03B03f3342E82DFB\" - showing Polymarket's official attribution of this token\n\n- The changelog says on April 17: \"Polymarket is shipping a coordinated upgrade: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (pUSD)\"\n\n- The migration guide says: \"Polymarket has shipped a coordinated upgrade of its entire trading infrastructure: new Exchange contracts, a rewritten CLOB backend, and a new collateral token (Polymarket USD, or pUSD)\"\n\n- The Help Center article says \"Polymarket is migrating from USDC.e to Polymarket USD (pUSD) as the collateral token\" and \"What is pUSD? pUSD is the new collateral token for Polymarket. It's a regular ERC-20 on Polygon, backed 1:1 by USDC.\"\n\nThe definition doesn't say \"a standalone token not used for collateral\" - it just says \"a fungible token officially released by Polymarket and publicly communicated through official Polymarket channels, excluding NFT launches, promotional offerings, tokenized point systems, and token launches in collaboration with other projects or communities.\" \n\nCollateral tokens are not excluded by the rule. In fact, the rule explicitly includes \"a fungible token\" without qualification that it must be an investment token or have certain characteristics beyond fungibility and official release by Polymarket.\n\nPolymarket's own communication consistently identifies it as \"a new collateral token\" but doesn't say it's \"not a token\" or \"not official\" or part of a collaboration. The only exclusions in the rule are NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration/community tokens. This appears to be none of those - it's Polymarket's own token, used for collateral, officially documented as Polymarket USD.\n\nIn the record, there is a distinction between \"technical collateral token\" and \"official fungible token\" being made by the defendant. But the rule doesn't define \"official fungible token\" to exclude collateral tokens. On the contrary, when Polymarket says it's releasing \"a new collateral token\" called \"Polymarket USD,\" that would seem to qualify as \"an official fungible token\" under the rule.\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I believe the proposition has been demonstrated.\n\nThe rationale needs to be concise - maximum 3 sentences.\n\nI should submit a vote of \"demonstrated\" with a brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2eebf19685194806afbde3","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Polymarket's official documentation consistently identifies pUSD as 'a new collateral token' and 'Polymarket USD' - a fungible ERC-20 token officially released by Polymarket and communicated through its public channels. The rule excludes only NFTs, promotional offerings, tokenized points, and collaboration tokens, which pUSD does not qualify as. The evidence demonstrates the proposition by a preponderance.\"}"}}],"api":"